<br>
There wasn't a school of magics around anywhere, so he knew there would be no mages among the group. The forest was dark, and there were few, if any, nature spirits left, so there would be no druids. He didn't even see barracks anywhere, just a few pikemen along the wall; oh yes, this was going to be tough.<br>
<br>
He remembered most of the faces that he'd seen that night; only a few of the recruits (children, actually) masked their fear as well as did a select few. He hoped against hope that there would be shady glory-seekers or beastlings or changelings or *some* kind of magical creature would hop along his path when he crossed the fields; anything to help him keep these children safe.<br>
<br>
&quot;My name is Dreyan. That's enough for now,&quot; He shouted. &quot;I can only take a few with you; we'll not be able to sneak in with a force of so many,&quot; he lied. He pointed to a late-arriving young man with a girl near him, one sneaky looking woman, a brutish man, and the girl earlier that, along with these three, showed him no fear. He hoped it would be enough. &quot;You four, come along. If the rest of you wish to help, build defenses in the plains. We leave now.&quot; He hopped off the rock he'd been standing on, and gathered the people he'd pointed out around him to hear their suggestions on the matter as they walked through the streets. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/ubellonakali.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bellona Kali</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Child of Hate</span><br>  Posts: 88<br> <font color=#FF0000>(6/17/02 8:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/ffantasystoriesforumfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://pmp.4t.com/magelo/smallbell.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Nothing to notice</span><hr size=1> Dreyan... What an odd name. His name did not matter, his ability to teach and guide these selected few did. Following behind the small group, Zita keeps her head down and her opinions silent. What did a small girl like her need to say? She was there, and she would try her hardest, that was all she had to offer. She tried to keep up with the conversations about tactics, but it was all so over her head that she often found herself lost. What * was * 'gorilla warfare' anyway? Zita knew it had nothing to do with apes, but what * was * if not a type of monkey war? Maybe she was not as far from the answer as she thought, but to her it seemed like they had hundreds of life times filled with wisdom, and 